# ⚡ Epilepsy

> **Epilepsy is a condition of recurrent unprovoked seizures arising from abnormal hypersynchronous neuronal discharge — classified by seizure type, EEG pattern, and underlying syndrome, with treatment targeted to specific mechanisms.**

## 🔗 Key Connections
- [[Neurotransmitters]] — GABA (inhibitory failure), glutamate (excitatory excess), T-type Ca²⁺ (absence)
- [[Synaptic Transmission]] — paroxysmal depolarization shift; NMDA/AMPA/GABA-A receptors
- [[Action Potential]] — Na⁺ channel (target of phenytoin/carbamazepine/lamotrigine)
- [[Cerebral Cortex]] — seizure origin and spread; cortical hyperexcitability
- [[Hippocampus]] — temporal lobe epilepsy; hippocampal sclerosis; déjà vu
- [[Thalamus]] — thalamo-cortical loop in absence epilepsy; 3 Hz spike-wave
- [[Neurodegenerative Diseases]] — seizures in late Alzheimer's; anti-NMDAR encephalitis
- [[Memory Systems]] — ictal/postictal amnesia; transient epileptic amnesia
- [[Glial Cells]] — astrocyte K⁺ buffering failure; reactive gliosis in sclerosis

## 🗂️ Key Information

| Property | Detail |
|----------|--------|
| Seizure definition | Paroxysmal, hypersynchronous, abnormal neuronal discharge → transient neurological symptoms |
| Epilepsy definition | ≥2 unprovoked seizures >24 h apart; OR 1 unprovoked + ≥60% recurrence risk; OR epilepsy syndrome |
| Provoked seizures | NOT epilepsy: fever, hypoglycaemia, hyponatraemia, hypoxia, alcohol withdrawal, drugs |
| Incidence | ~50/100,000/year; lifetime prevalence 1-2% |
| Classification system | ILAE 2017: focal / generalised / unknown onset |

