## 🔑 Pathophysiology

### Paroxysmal Depolarization Shift (PDS)
- Large sustained membrane depolarization + burst firing in seizure focus
- Driven by: ↑NMDA/AMPA glutamate activation, ↑Na⁺/Ca²⁺ influx, ↓K⁺/Cl⁻ conductance
- Normally surrounded by **inhibitory surround** (GABA-mediated, K⁺ hyperpolarization)
- Seizure = loss of surround inhibition + recurrent excitation spreading through network

### Seizure Termination
- Postictal suppression: synaptic depression, adenosine release (A1 receptor), enhanced GABA, K⁺ accumulation (astrocyte buffering failure in SE)

### Absence Mechanism (Thalamo-Cortical Loop)
```
Cortex → thalamic relay neurons (excitation)
    ↓
Thalamic reticular nucleus (GABA-B) → prolonged inhibition of relay neurons
    ↓
Low-threshold T-type Ca²⁺ channels → rebound burst firing
    ↓
3 Hz spike-wave oscillation ← ← ← (loop)
Ethosuximide blocks T-type Ca²⁺ → breaks loop
```

### Contributing Factors
- Astrocyte K⁺ buffering failure (↑extracellular K⁺ → neuronal hyperexcitability)
- Gap junction coupling (electrical spread)
- Loss of inhibitory interneurons (e.g., hippocampal sclerosis: parvalbumin interneuron loss)
- Channelopathies (Na⁺, K⁺, Ca²⁺, Cl⁻ mutations in genetic epilepsies)

