## 🔑 ILAE 2017 Seizure Classification

### Focal Onset (one hemisphere network)
- **Focal aware** (consciousness preserved): aura only — sensory, motor, autonomic, psychic (déjà vu, fear, rising epigastric sensation)
- **Focal impaired awareness** (formerly complex partial): automatisms, post-ictal confusion
- **Focal to bilateral tonic-clonic**: secondary generalisation (formerly secondarily generalised)

### Generalised Onset (bilateral networks from start)
| Type | Consciousness | Key Features |
|------|--------------|-------------|
| **Typical absence** | Impaired (blank stare) | Brief <30 s; no postictal; eye blinking; 3 Hz spike-wave |
| **Myoclonic** | Preserved | Brief bilateral jerks; morning predominance; polyspike-wave |
| **Tonic-clonic (GTCS)** | Lost | Tonic (10-20 s) → clonic (1-2 min) → postictal confusion; tongue bite (lateral); incontinence |
| **Tonic** | Lost | Sustained stiffening; common in Lennox-Gastaut |
| **Atonic (drop attacks)** | Brief loss | Sudden muscle tone loss → fall; injury risk |
| **Myoclonic-atonic** | Variable | Myoclonic jerk then atonic drop; Doose syndrome |
| **Epileptic spasms** | Variable | Flexion/extension clusters; West syndrome (infantile) |

### Unknown Onset
- Tonic-clonic of unknown onset, epileptic spasms of unknown onset

