## 🔑 Major Epilepsy Syndromes

### Childhood Absence Epilepsy (CAE)
- Age 4-8 years; girls > boys; 3 Hz generalised spike-wave
- Frequent brief absences (>10/day); no postictal state; staring + subtle automatisms
- Treatment: ethosuximide (first-line CAE) or valproate; lamotrigine second-line
- Prognosis: most remit in adolescence (unlike JME)

### Juvenile Myoclonic Epilepsy (JME)
- Adolescence; morning myoclonus (arms) + GTCS ± absences; photosensitive
- EEG: 3.5-5 Hz generalised polyspike-wave
- **LIFELONG** condition (relapses if medication stopped); valproate (most effective but teratogenic); levetiracetam; lamotrigine (may worsen myoclonus at high doses)

### West Syndrome
- Infantile spasms (3-12 months); hypsarrhythmia on EEG; developmental regression
- Causes: tuberous sclerosis (TSC), Down syndrome, HIE, structural cortical malformations
- Treatment: ACTH (first-line); vigabatrin (first-line for TSC — GABA-T inhibitor)
- Poor prognosis: evolves to Lennox-Gastaut in ~50%

### Lennox-Gastaut Syndrome (LGS)
- Childhood; multiple seizure types (tonic, atonic/drop, absence) + slow (<2.5 Hz) spike-wave + intellectual disability
- Refractory; valproate + rufinamide + clobazam; dietary (ketogenic); VNS; corpus callosotomy for drop attacks

### Mesial Temporal Lobe Epilepsy (mTLE)
- Most common partial epilepsy in adults; hippocampal sclerosis (HS) most common cause
- Hippocampal sclerosis: neuronal loss + gliosis in CA1 (Sommer's sector), CA3, dentate hilus; parvalbumin interneuron loss; mossy fibre sprouting
- **Semiology**: aura (rising epigastric sensation, déjà vu/jamais vu, fear, olfactory hallucinations), oral automatisms (lip smacking, chewing), manual automatisms, ipsilateral dystonic posturing of arm, postictal confusion + aphasia (dominant hemisphere)
- MRI: hippocampal atrophy + ↑T2/FLAIR signal + loss of internal architecture on coronal cuts
- Surgical outcome: ~70% seizure-free (Engel class I) with temporal lobectomy

### Dravet Syndrome
- SCN1A mutation (Nav1.1 — loss-of-function in inhibitory interneurons → network hyperexcitability)
- Febrile-triggered prolonged GTCS in first year → multiple seizure types, cognitive regression
- **Avoid**: Na⁺ channel blockers (carbamazepine, lamotrigine, phenytoin — worsen seizures)
- Treatment: valproate + clobazam; stiripentol; cannabidiol (Epidiolex); fenfluramine

### Anti-NMDAR Encephalitis
- Anti-GluN1 (NR1) antibodies; associated with ovarian teratoma (young women)
- Sequence: psychiatric prodrome (psychosis, agitation) → seizures → movement disorders (orofacial dyskinesias, stereotypies) → autonomic instability → coma
- CSF: lymphocytic pleocytosis; MRI often normal or hippocampal T2
- Treatment: immunotherapy (steroids, IVIG, plasmapheresis) + teratoma removal; rituximab/cyclophosphamide if refractory

