## 🔑 Antiepileptic Drug Mechanisms

| Drug | Mechanism | Spectrum | Key Side Effects / Notes |
|------|-----------|---------|--------------------------|
| **Phenytoin** | Na⁺ channel use-dependent inactivation | Focal, GTCS; NOT absence | Zero-order kinetics; gingival hyperplasia; hirsutism; SJS; teratogenic (fetal hydantoin syndrome) |
| **Carbamazepine** | Na⁺ channel | Focal, GTCS, trigeminal neuralgia | Diplopia, hyponatraemia (SIADH), SJS (HLA-B*1502 in Han Chinese/Thai); strong P450 inducer |
| **Valproate** | Na⁺ channel + T-Ca²⁺ + ↑GABA (GABA-T inhibition) | Broad spectrum (absence, myoclonic, GTCS, focal) | Teratogenic (neural tube defects 1-2%); weight gain; tremor; hepatotoxicity; pancreatitis; thrombocytopenia; avoid in women of childbearing age |
| **Ethosuximide** | T-type Ca²⁺ channel (thalamic relay neurons) | **Absence ONLY** | GI upset; headache; no effect on focal/GTCS |
| **Lamotrigine** | Na⁺ channel + ↓glutamate release | Focal, GTCS, absence, bipolar | SJS (↑risk with valproate — slow titration essential); insomnia; safest in pregnancy (folate supplementation) |
| **Levetiracetam** | SV2A synaptic vesicle protein (↓neurotransmitter release) | Broad spectrum | Behavioural (irritability, aggression, depression) — most common dose-limiting; no P450 interactions |
| **Topiramate** | Na⁺ channel + AMPA/kainate + GABA-A + carbonic anhydrase | Focal, GTCS, migraine prophylaxis | Cognitive slowing ("dopamax"), word-finding; kidney stones; metabolic acidosis; angle-closure glaucoma; weight loss |
| **Oxcarbazepine** | Na⁺ channel (active metabolite licarbazepine) | Focal, trigeminal neuralgia | Better tolerated than CBZ; hyponatraemia; less P450 induction |
| **Lacosamide** | Na⁺ channel slow inactivation (novel mechanism) | Focal (adjunct), GTCS | PR prolongation; dizziness; IV formulation available |
| **Gabapentin / Pregabalin** | α2δ subunit of VGCC (↓Ca²⁺ at presynaptic terminals) | Focal (adjunct), neuropathic pain, anxiety (pregabalin) | Sedation; weight gain; dizziness; gabapentin requires active transporter for GI absorption (dose-dependent bioavailability) |
| **Benzodiazepines** (diazepam, lorazepam, midazolam, clonazepam) | GABA-A positive allosteric modulator (↑frequency of Cl⁻ channel opening) | Acute seizure; status epilepticus; anxiety | Sedation; respiratory depression; tolerance; dependence; IM midazolam if no IV access |
| **Phenobarbital** | GABA-A (↑duration of Cl⁻ channel opening) + ↓glutamate | Broad; neonatal seizures | Sedation; cognitive effects in children; paradoxical hyperactivity; strong P450 inducer |
| **Vigabatrin** | Irreversible GABA transaminase (GABA-T) inhibitor → ↑GABA | Infantile spasms (esp. TSC); focal (adjunct) | **Permanent peripheral visual field constriction** (30-40%); irreversible; regular ophthalmology |
| **Rufinamide** | Na⁺ channel (prolongs inactivation) | Lennox-Gastaut (atonic/tonic) | QT shortening (contraindicated short QT) |
| **Cannabidiol (Epidiolex)** | Uncertain — multiple targets (GPR55, TRPV1, adenosine) | Dravet syndrome; LGS; TSC | Somnolence; ↑liver enzymes (with valproate); GI upset |
| **Fenfluramine** | Serotonin-releasing; 5-HT2C agonism | Dravet syndrome | Cardiac monitoring required (historical valvulopathy at high doses) |

