## 🔑 Status Epilepticus (SE)

**Definition**: seizure >5 minutes OR ≥2 seizures without return to baseline

### Treatment Protocol
| Time | Stage | Treatment |
|------|-------|-----------|
| 0-5 min | Stabilisation | Airway, O₂, IV access, glucose, vitals, EEG monitoring |
| 5-20 min | Early SE | **Lorazepam** 0.1 mg/kg IV (preferred) OR IM midazolam 10 mg (if no IV) |
| 20-40 min | Established SE | **Fosphenytoin** 20 mg PE/kg IV OR **Levetiracetam** 60 mg/kg IV OR **Valproate** 40 mg/kg IV |
| 40-60 min | Refractory SE | Intubation + **propofol** infusion OR **midazolam** infusion; continuous EEG |
| >60 min | Super-refractory SE | **Pentobarbital** (burst-suppression target); ketamine; hypothermia; immunotherapy if encephalitis |

- **Non-convulsive SE (NCSE)**: altered mental status only — diagnosis requires EEG; treat aggressively (neuronal damage occurs despite no convulsions)
- Complications of prolonged GTCS-SE: hyperthermia, rhabdomyolysis, respiratory failure, excitotoxic neuronal death, lactic acidosis

