## 🏥 Clinical Significance

| Condition | Key Facts | Management |
|-----------|----------|------------|
| Temporal lobe epilepsy + HS | Most common adult partial epilepsy; surgical cure available | AEDs first (CBZ/OXC); temporal lobectomy if drug-resistant |
| Juvenile myoclonic epilepsy | Lifelong; morning myoclonus + GTCS; photosensitive | Valproate (most effective); levetiracetam if concerns |
| Absence epilepsy | 3 Hz spike-wave; ethosuximide first-line CAE | Ethosuximide; valproate; lamotrigine |
| West syndrome | Infantile spasms + hypsarrhythmia; poor prognosis | ACTH; vigabatrin (TSC) |
| Dravet syndrome | SCN1A; avoid Na⁺ channel blockers | Valproate + clobazam; stiripentol; cannabidiol |
| Anti-NMDAR encephalitis | Ovarian teratoma; psychiatric onset; movement disorder | Immunotherapy + tumour removal |
| Febrile seizures | <5% develop epilepsy; simple vs complex | Reassurance (simple); investigate (complex) |
| Eclampsia | Seizure in pregnancy/postpartum + hypertension | IV magnesium sulphate (first-line); delivery |
| Status epilepticus | >5 min or repeated without recovery | Benzodiazepine → second-line IV AED → anaesthetic infusion |

